        Official Singles Chart on 29/11/2019

        29 November 2019 - 5 December 2019

        The Official UK Singles Chart reflects the UKs biggest songs of the week, based on audio and video streams, downloads, CDs and vinyl, compiled by the Official Charts Company. The UK Top 40 is broadcast on BBC Radio 1 and MTV, the Top 100 is published exclusively on OfficialCharts.com. View the biggest songs of 2024 so far.

        My 2010 throwback review.
        1. Timbaland feat. Justin Timberlake: Carry Out. This has without a doubt got to be one of my favourite songs from Spring that year. I really like listening to that song. Infact Timbaland and Justin Timberlake have actually done some really good songs to be honest but Carry Out has got to be their best one in my opinion
        2. Ne-yo: Beautiful Monster. Another one of my favourite songs from 2010. This was a good song to be played in clubs and this is very different especially for a Ne-yo song. It was #1 in the UK charts in August of that year. It also has a very good video.
        3. Jason Derulo: In My Head. This is a really good song from Jason Derulo. The video to it sort of reminds of Justin Timberlakes Like I Love You video. Also in the video he dances a bit like Michael Jackson although he was inspired by Michael Jackson. The only two differences about the video to In my Head and the video to Justin Timberlakes Like I love you is that In My Head is mostly filmed outside the store and the video to Justin Timberlakes Like I Love You is fimed in Various Locations. Both Videos were filmed outside the same store. As for the song itself, it is a really good song and it has really good beat to it. Perfect for nightclubs.

        4.Professor Green feat. Ed Drewett: I Need You Tonight. I love this song it samples Need You Tonight by INXS and I think it is brilliant the song got to #3 in April 2010 and I can't of anything else to say about it.
        5. Rihanna: Only Girl in the World: In my opinion, this has got to be one of her best songs and it was #1 single. The song has a really good beat to it and I like to head bang to it. This also the time when Rihanna had red hair.
        6. Tinie Tempah: Pass Out. I love this song. I think it is really good and I do listen to it alot. It is a pure banger and Labrinth is also in the song but uncredited. the video is also quite good. It got to #1 in March 2010.

        I review everything hot inside and bubbling just under the top 40, and we actually have quite the interesting range of tracks today - from Britain's finest hip-hop, to its not so finest, from Canadian R&B, back to the UK with an indie band, and even a soundtrack single! Without further ado, let's get started.

        (NEW ENTRY) #03: STORMZY feat. ED SHEERAN and BURNA BOY - OWN IT
        This is the type of track that captures me from the very first listen, which actually doesn't happen very often let's go a bit more in depth. For as much as Stormzy is unarguably one of the biggest names in UK urban music currently, and I've always respected his music, I could never really get behind it. "Big For Your Boots", one of his biggest songs, was actually not bad, but "Vossi Bop" was mostly forgettable for me, with recent follow-ups managing to impress me, but without much longevity. This however? Oh, this is fantastic. I love the club-ier tone the production sets, very different from most of his other tracks, which might be a big factor as to why I like this so much. Stormzy and Ed still have amazing chemistry, but I need to also mention Burna Boy, whose voice is an incredible addition and fits the beat great. I think my only complaint would have to be that this is a bit too short, haha! Overall, I'm going to give this a strong 9/10, which is actually the highest score I've given to a song ever since I started doing these reviews! Who would've thought a Stormzy and Ed Sheeran song would have this honor.

        akyovbashiev

        29th November 2019
        3
        Vote score

        (NEW ENTRY) #16: DIGDAT feat. D-BLOCK EUROPE - NEW DIOR
        On the other side of the UK urban spectrum, we have D-Block Europe and as divisive as I am on them generally, their tracks usually end up growing on me at the end. DigDat, however, has previously had five songs make the top 75, four of which I have thoroughly enjoyed (the fifth one I haven't heard). Straight off the bat with this, the chorus, sung by Young Adz, I think it's trying to build up to something it can't really live up to, though it did grow on me throughout the song, and the production is pretty good as well. However, it's DigDat that really throws me off here - his flow is generally a bit weirder, and while it has worked for most of his other work, it really feels kinda odd here for some reason. I think that really shows at the transitions from his verse to Young Adz' chorus, which I also should mention suits the beat better, in my opinion. I'm still incredibly divided on this song, but I feel like it has the potential to grow on me, so I'm going with a strong 6/10 for now.

        akyovbashiev

        (NEW ENTRY) #31: PARTYNEXTDOOR feat. DRAKE - LOYAL
        I first heard this track on the Sunday First Look show on Radio 1 and it felt a bit weird, but I guess as with most songs for me, it took a second hearing to get it right. It's obvious this is absolutely nothing extraordinary as far as R&B is concerned, and is only here because of the "feat. Drake", which, before I go on with the review, I have to mention, is in itself incredible that one artist can have so much name power that he can get a song from going under the radar to top 40 hit. Anyways, I don't usually comment on this, as it's a factor with most urban songs and usually doesn't matter, but here it sticks out a lot: this track barely has any structure. I got lost listening to it even the second time, and I couldn't really make out what was the chorus (if any), what was the verse, and if not for the Drake feature, this probably could have passed for a freestyle. PARTYNEXTDOOR's vocals are fine for the most part, but largely outshined by Drake's, and the production is there, I suppose. I'm very picky with R&B generally, which is why I'm going so hard on this, and that's the reason I'm gonna have to give it a 5/10, unfortunately.

        (NEW ENTRY) #35: ZIEZIE feat. AITCH - FRENCH KISSES
        To begin with, I just want to say, I'm impressed how they're running with the French theme throughout the entire song, it's not just a random word thrown in the title and mentioned once, the music video is actually set in Paris and ZieZie goes on to do a small bit in French, which was kinda cool.         My thoughts & observations on the UK charts as always

        Dance Monkey by Tones & I becomes the longest running #1 single of 2019 so far, with a ninth consecutive week on top! It racked up 9.58 million streams over the past seven days, as well as being the most downloaded track of the week.

        Dont Start Now by Dua Lipa was the most played song on British radio over the past week!

        Dance Monkey also spends a seventh week in a row as the countrys most watched YouTube video, although it does decline 10.5% in views, down to 4.38 million for the tracking week!

        STORMZY FT ED SHEERAN & BURNA BOY - OWN IT (#3)
        While the chart run of Take Me Back To London got me tired of the song quicker than most, I still stand by saying that the original was one of the best tracks from No.6 Collaborations Project & a fantastic ambassador to grime music in bringing the genres success to other countries! Following on from that, I was looking forward to what Ed & Stormzys third collaboration would bring which is unfortunately not a lot! Yeah, I dig Stormzys more chilled delivery on the opening hook of the song & he can ride the groove well, but his content seemed ridiculously repetitive, especially since hes usually such a lyrical mastermind! While Ed is at least more creative with his presentation, he still feels somewhat out of place here & not as comfortable as weve heard from his other his this year. Factor all of that in & you barely notice that Burna Boy is even here, who harmonises with Stormzy earlier in the song, but hes pushed so far back in the otherwise messy mix that I can hardly hear him at all! Again, I still have a lot of respect for a majority of things all three of these artists have done, but I sadly cant put this among them. Solid 5/10 here!

        DIGDAT FT D-BLOCK EUROPE - NEW DIOR (#16)
        Im not even going to talk about this one for very long, since Ive already said the same thing about D-Block Europe six times before, you get the message! Production with absolutely no substance, minimal effort in their delivery, weak adlibs, even DigDat outshining them here! Maybe the gentle groove deep down in the song which stands out near the end is the only attraction here, because its very clear that the writing shows no signs of developing, especially when the first notable line (which Im not even going to repeat) is about having $ex with girls instead of caring about them! In other words, another week, another drill debut we can dismiss almost immediately. Solid 3/10!

        PARTYNEXTDOOR FT DRAKE - LOYAL (#31)
        It might have been a while since many people would consider PARTYNEXTDOOR relevant, but honestly, I wouldve expected his comeback to be with none other than regular collaborator, Drake. As for this, on first listen, I actually feel this is something I could very easily warm to with time! Despite three producers working on this, the tropical-pop tone & even the auto-tuned vocals remain intact throughout the entire song, where PARTYNEXTDOOR can also vibe with Drake rather pleasantly here. I do feel that this does take a bit of time to get properly going, as well as fading out, but from the main body that we do get, I did like this a lot more than I was expecting. Obviously, my rating can change a lot this early on, but right now, strong 6/10!

        Just interrupting the flow of covering new entries, its so awesome to see All I Want For Christmas Is You back in late November! Hopefully thisll be the year it goes all the way to #1!

        ZIEZIE FT AITCH - FRENCH KISSES (#35)
        I honestly didnt know what to expect going into this one, since Aitch & ZieZie have never really captured my interest on their own, although they actually produced impressive results when they recently collaborated on Buss Down, which has only grown on me even more since I reviewed it here! As for this, no, Im sorry, the same thing just isnt going to happen. I mean, I actually got intrigued by the French-style introduction, but the transition to a blocky trap beat seemed incredibly turbulent, then we get ZieZie who sounds a lot more trembly than usual (at least in English, because his brief French delivery actually didnt sound bad). Other than that, he just sounds really boring, where even Aitch sounds a bit more engaged for at least being slightly charismatic. Even then, all the content is about is trying to make out with the girl, which is probably the most predictable lyrical approach from Aitch. Overall, there was potential for this to work, but it sadly got ruined by bland performances across the board. For that, light 4/10!

        IDINA MENZEL FT AURORA - INTO THE UNKNOWN (#36)
        So look, for as annoyingly overplayed as Let It Go was six years ago, it had an anthemic hook that was impossible not to sing along to! It certainly had the magic to become arguably one of the biggest Disney songs of the decade. Unfortunately, you can tell this song is trying to follow a very similar formula, which sadly fails to impress anywhere near as much! I do like the playful pianos that open the song, but the whispery, spoken vocals have never been a winning point for any of the Frozen soundtrack songs, but theyre somehow even worse here as the upper register is a lot weaker in general. Theres certainly potential when the strings & knocks kick in the second verse, since you get interesting switches of dynamic, but the hook still falls really flat for me! Also, while Let It Go was such a defining motivational anthem, the content here is just about not venturing into unknown territory, but with the mysterious feel of the song as a whole only partly getting there! So yeah, I see the appeal, but Im probably going to forget this even exists by next week. On that note, light 5/10!

        BASTILLE FT LONDON CONTEMPORARY ORCHESTRA - CANT FIGHT THIS FEELING (#39)
        Its hard not to find John Lewis Christmas advert songs absolutely adorable, especially with the videos attached to them! That said, I have to review this as a song by itself, which even then is still mostly enjoyable. Dan Smiths vocals are the centerpoint of how beautiful & sentimental this cover is, which is well accompanied with the violins courtesy of the London Contemporary Orchestra. In fact, all the string instrumentals from them capture the emotion from Dan in a very touching & stunning manner, as well as the timpani really driving the power behind this. My only nitpick would be that this cover doesnt really allow the other members of Bastille to stand out, but thats been a criticism Ive always had with their music in general! Overall though, while it doesnt beat the original for me, I do hope this can climb in the weeks building up to Christmas. Therefore, light 8/10!

        On the albums chart, Coldplay continue their perfect streak, as Everyday Life scores them their eighth #1 with the third biggest debut of 2019 so far (81,000 combined chart sales!).

        The rest of the Top 5 is: The Christmas Present by Robbie Williams (debuts at #2, 67,000 chart sales), Youre In My Heart by Rod Stewart & The Royal Philharmonic Orchestra (debuts at #3), Divinely Uninspired To A Hellish Extent by Lewis Capaldi (stationary at #4) & Back Together by Michael Ball & Alfie Boe (3-5).

        While Robbie Williams didnt achieve the top spot this week, he does have the fastest-selling album on cassette since NOW 52 in July 2002! All of Robbies solo studio albums have charted within the Top 2.

        Looking ahead to next week, these songs could enter the Top 40 for the first time: Heartless & Blinding Lights by The Weeknd, Up All Night by Khalid & maybe even more.

        Thanks for reading everyone! I hope you all have a good weekend. :)

        Hey Piran! It's cool to see 'Dance Monkey' get a 9th consecutive week at #1, though I never would've guessed it'd come even close to that amount when it first reached #1! I really like seeing 'Before You Go' shoot up to #2 on its first full week on the chart, and 'ROXANNE' climbing in the Top 10 was good to see. 'This Is Real', 'Watermelon Sugar' and 'Better Half Of Me' all climbing to new peaks is cool as well, though it is disappointing to see 'Circles' hit ACR with that massive drop.
        The debuts this week were a mixed bag for me. Obviously it'll be no surprise that I absolutely love 'Own It', and that it's my favourite debut of the week by a huge margin! I can definitely see where you're coming from with regards to Burna Boy's vocals being pushed back in the mix, but that doesn't really put me off the song at all, and I still like his parts in the chorus and first verse, and I love the more chilled vibe that this song gives off, as well as both Stormzy & Ed's vocals throughout the song. Yeah, solid - strong 10/10 for me on this one! 'New Dior' was just boring for me, so a strong 4/10 for this one, while I was somewhat disappointed by 'Loyal', especially with PARTYNEXTDOOR's vocals, but I did still kind of like the beat & Drake's vocals, so a light 6/10 here. 'French Kisses' was nowhere near as good as 'Buss Down' for me, just a light 5/10 for this, and 'Into The Unknown' couldn't match 'Let It Go' for me either - solid 4/10 for this one. Lastly, I don't mind 'Can't Fight This Feeling', but it's not really my type of music, so a solid 6/10 here.
        Next week it looks like the Christmas tracks will come rocketing up the charts yet again, but I think the Top 3 will remain entirely unchanged. 'Dance Monkey' is still ruling Spotify, YouTube and Deezer, and while it's at #2 on iTunes, it's behind an X Factor track with no streaming behind it so that won't be a threat. The interesting one comes from Apple Music, where 'Dance Monkey' is at #2 behind 'Own It' - I still think the latter will be #3 in the next chart, but its chances of being the Christmas #1 seem to be getting better and better! The Weeknd's tracks are definitely doing better than I expected, so they should both be pretty big debuts, but I think almost every other potential debut will be washed away by Christmas tracks.
